05168nam a22007455i 9780824865665DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20052005hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248656657 a10.1515/97808248656652doi  a(DE-B1597)483889  a(OCoLC)1024008609  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aBQ9262.9.B6bR63 2006 7aREL0920002bisacsh04a294.3/9270981222  aBE 85092rvk0(DE-625)rvk/10756:1 aRocha, Cristina, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aZen in Brazil :bThe Quest for Cosmopolitan Modernity /cCristina Rocha. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b24 illus., 2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTopics in Contemporary Buddhism ;v2300tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tSeries Editor’s Preface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Japanese-Brazilian Junction: Establishing Zen Missions -- t2. Non-Japanese Brazilians and the Orientalist Shaping of Zen -- t3. The Brazilian Religious Field: Where does Zen Fit In? -- t4. The Brazilian Imaginary of Zen: Global Influences, Rhizomatic Forms -- t5 Doing Zen, Being Zen: Creolizing ‘‘Ethnic’’ and ‘‘Convert’’ Buddhism -- tConclusion Translocal Flows: The ‘‘Meditodrome’’ as a Zen Style of Governing -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWidely perceived as an overwhelmingly Catholic nation, Brazil has experienced in recent years a growth in the popularity of Buddhism among the urban, cosmopolitan upper classes. In the 1990s Buddhism in general and Zen in particular were adopted by national elites, the media, and popular culture as a set of humanistic values to counter the rampant violence and crime in Brazilian society. Despite national media attention, the rapidly expanding Brazilian market for Buddhist books and events, and general interest in the globalization of Buddhism, the Brazilian case has received little scholarly attention. Cristina Rocha addresses that shortcoming in Zen in Brazil. Drawing on fieldwork in Japan and Brazil, she examines Brazilian history, culture, and literature to uncover the mainly Catholic, Spiritist, and Afro-Brazilian religious matrices responsible for this particular indigenization of Buddhism. In her analysis of Japanese immigration and the adoption and creolization of the Sôtôshû school of Zen Buddhism in Brazil, she offers the fascinating insight that the latter is part of a process of "cannibalizing" the modern other to become modern oneself. She shows, moreover, that in practicing Zen, the Brazilian intellectual elites from the 1950s onward have been driven by a desire to acquire and accumulate cultural capital both locally and overseas. Their consumption of Zen, Rocha contends, has been an expression of their desire to distinguish themselves from popular taste at home while at the same time associating themselves with overseas cultural elites.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aJapanesezBrazilxReligion. 0aZen BuddhismzBrazilxHistory. 0aZen BuddhismzJapanxHistory. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / Zen (see also PHILOSOPHY / Zen).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082486566540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824865665423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824865665/original  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d201